tspan.tspan: Figure Y: host genotype differentiation of gut microbiome.
A) Change of alpha diversity (Faith's Phylogenetic Diversity) over generations.
Diversity of six individual embryo recipient mother (RM) mice of mixed genotype B6CF1 (gray), housed in three cages is given as the red box
and circles. Following line plots summarize the diversity of six offspring generations (P to F5), which were inbreed in three fully separated
cage lineages per genotype (C57BL6/J in blue and BALB/c in orange). Diversity of six control mice per genotype and per independent
environments (Duesseldorf and Janvier) is visualized as four boxes and circles on the right hand side. Top x axis labels indicate number of
individual mice (i), number of cages (c) in which mice were housed and number of cage lineages (l). B) Beta diversity distance (measured as
weighted UniFrac) to RM samples. Line plots summarize distance of C57BLK6/J and BALB/C samples to RM samples, in blue and orange,
respectively. Green line plot indicates distance between both genotypes. For reference, the gray dashed line is the mean pairwise distance
between individuals housed in the same cage, i.e. lower resolution limit as these mice should be biological replicates. Brown dotted line is
the mean distance of individuals from two different cages (1,323 individual pairs: i-i) of the same genotype, cage lineage and generation.
Significance is assessed via PERMANOVA tests with 999 permutations. C) Beta diversity distance (measured as weighted UniFrac) to control

text.tspan: samples as a proxy of environment. Solid lines stand for control mice from Duesseldorf (Germany), dashed lines from Janvier (France). D)
Microbiome distance (measured as unweighted UniFrac) between offspring and true dam (blue and orange boxes for C57BL6/J and BALB/c,
respectively) and between offspring and dam of same genotype but different cage lineage (gray boxes) and between offspring and dam of
